If government officials want to take credit only when things go well, they should convert their offices into praise-and-worship cubicles so that Kenyans can seek help from witchdoctors whenever we are in trouble.
Doctors took an oath to save lives, not to die from government negligence. Otherwise they would have told the BBI task force as much, but all they said was that they wanted was a Health Service Commission.
We know government policymakers have had problems with hearing the plight of Kenyans, but it can’t be so bad as to confuse a Health Service Commission with a Health Slavery Commission.
Mr Oguda comments on topical issues; gabriel.oguda@gmail.com He served in former president Daniel Moi's cabinet. BBI secretariat cleaned up the 5.2 million signatures that endorsed the Bill, and weeded out 800,000 that had entry irregularities. This comes days after he collapsed at a hotel in Nairobi and was placed under intensive care at Nairobi Hospital.